04173nam a22005295i 9781847427762DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818474277627 a10.56687/97818474277622doi  a(DE-B1597)646475  a(OCoLC)609852100  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 4aHQ796 7aSOC0470002bisacsh04a305.235qOCoLC222/eng/202302161 aThomson, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnfolding lives :bYouth, gender and change /cRachel Thomson. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tThe breadth and depth of youth transitions -- tA method-in-practice: constructing longitudinal case histories -- tGender and social change -- tGoing up! Discipline and opportunism -- tGoing down? Caught between stasis and mobility -- tComing out: from the closet to stepping stones -- tActing out: rebellion with a cause -- tInterruption: from explanation to understanding -- tConversation: reading between the lines -- tYouth, gender and change -- tThe case history data sets -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe process of becoming an adult in contemporary times is fragmented and unequal, shaped by chance, choice and timing. Unfolding lives presents a unique approach to understanding the changing face of youth transitions, addressing the question of how gender identities are constituted in late modern culture. The book follows individual lives over time, enabling the reader to witness gender identities in the making and breathing new life into static analytic models. At the heart of the book are vivid in-depth accounts of four young lives, emblematic of broader biographical trends. They reveal how inequalities and privileges are made in new and unexpected ways, through practices such as falling in love, coming out, acting out and religious conversion. A focus on temporal processes and changing meanings captures what it feels like to be young and shows the creative ways that young people navigate the conflicting and changing demands of personal relationships, schooling, work and play. Unfolding lives is also a demonstration of a method-in-practice, describing how longitudinal material can be analysed and animated to realise the relationship between personal and social change. Written in an accessible style that breaks the conventional academic mould, Unfolding lives is a compelling and provocative read. The book will be an essential text for students and academics involved in youth and gender studies as well as those interested in new directions in qualitative research methods and writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGender identity. 0aYouthxConduct of life. 0aYouthxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z97831111962130 cprintz978184742902540uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781847427762?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847427762423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847427762/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles